          "reviewNotes": "Both agents contributed distinct, non-overlapping value across the full pipeline. openspec converted 7 vague originals into 13 well-scoped criteria — adding column names, API endpoint contracts, CDN constraint specifics, CSS custom property approach for dark mode, and label/title accessibility baseline. speckit retained all 13 and added 7 substantive criteria covering: (1) URL encoding precision, (2) loading indicator covering both success AND error resolution paths, (3) /cheapest parity gaps (loading state and error handling that openspec omitted), (4) XSS safety via safe DOM methods — the most security-critical addition, (5) double-submit prevention, (6) stale-result clearing, (7) thead/th accessibility, and (8) aria-live region. Cross-referencing against server.ts confirms AC-6's data.flights.length check is accurate — /search returns { flights, count, searchedAt } at line 81-85, so the envelope shape is correct. The /cheapest endpoint returns a single flight object directly (line 123), which aligns with AC-11's summary-section fallback. One minor precision issue: AC-1 says 'served as a static file' but server.ts uses readFileSync + manual send rather than express.static() middleware — functionally equivalent but the phrasing could mislead an implementer toward adding a redundant express.static() call. speckit's notes flagged two items needing human decisions (/cheapest-before-search UX and envelope shape mismatch) but the envelope concern is resolved by the actual server code, and the pre-search /cheapest path is implicitly covered by AC-10 (HTTP error → user message, since empty form fields yield a 400). No blocking gaps; 20 ACs are comprehensive and independently testable with no overlaps.",
